In [[Japanese mythology]], the story of the {{nihongo|birth of the gods|神産み|'''Kamiumi'''}} occurs after the creation of Japan (''[[Kuniumi]]'') and refers to the birth of the ''[[kami]]'', descendants of [[Izanagi]] and [[Izanami]].

==Story==
[[File:Creation myths of Japan 3-eng.svg|thumb|400px|Genealogy of Izanagi and Izanami according to the [[Kojiki]]]]
According to the [[Kojiki]], various gods were born from the relationship between Izanagi and Izanami until the fire deity, [[Kagutsuchi]], at birth burned Izanami's genitals and wounded her fatally.<ref name="kojiki-p77-78"/><ref name="kojiki-p79"/> Izanagi, witnessing the death of his beloved wife, in rage took the ten-grasp<ref group="nb" name="grasp">A "grasp" is the breadth of four fingers when the hand is clenched.</ref> sabre and crushed his child, Kagutsuchi.<ref name="kojiki-p80-81"/> A number of gods were born from the blood and remains of Kagutsuchi.<ref name="kojiki-p80-81"/> Subsequently, Izanagi went to the land of [[Yomi]] (the world of the dead) to find Izanami, however when he found her, she had become a rotting corpse and from her parts other gods had arisen, causing the flight of Izanagi to the world of the living.<ref name="kojiki-p82-83"/> Then Izanagi performed the [[misogi]] [[ritual purification]] through which more gods are born.<ref name="kojiki-p84-85"/>  The last of these are the three most important gods of [[Shinto]]: [[Amaterasu]], goddess of the sun; [[Tsukuyomi]], deity of the moon; and [[Susanoo]], god of the sea.<ref name="kojiki-p86"/>

